    {
      "question_number": 1,
      "question_text": "Correlation means:",
      "attempted": 2,
      "data_i18n": null,
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "Two variables have a statistical association",
          "is_correct": true,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "One variable causes the other",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Variables are independent",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Data is randomly distributed",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        }
      ],
      "explanation": "Correlation means two variables have a statistical association — they change together in a predictable way. The other options — 'One variable causes the other', 'Variables are independent', and 'Data is randomly distributed' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question."
    },
    {
      "question_number": 2,
      "question_text": "Causation means:",
      "attempted": 2,
      "data_i18n": null,
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "One variable directly causes a change in another",
          "is_correct": true,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Two variables are associated",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "Variables move in opposite directions",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "There is no relationship",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        }
      ],
      "explanation": "Causation means one variable directly causes a change in another. Correlation means two variables have a statistical association — they change together in a predictable way. The other options — 'Two variables are associated', 'Variables move in opposite directions', and 'There is no relationship' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question."
    },
    {
      "question_number": 3,
      "question_text": "A lurking variable is:",
      "attempted": 2,
      "data_i18n": null,
      "options": [
        {
          "text": "A hidden variable that may explain an observed association",
          "is_correct": true,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "The independent variable",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "The dependent variable",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        },
        {
          "text": "The correlation coefficient",
          "is_correct": false,
          "data_i18n": null
        }
      ],
      "explanation": "Correlation does not imply causation. A lurking (confounding) variable may cause both variables to change together without a direct causal relationship between them. The answer is 'A hidden variable that may explain an observed association'. The other options — 'The independent variable', 'The dependent variable', and 'The correlation coefficient' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question."
    },
